"Mavris C., Plötze M., Mirabella A., Giaccai D., Valboa G., Egli s M.","Clay mineral evolution along a soil chronosequence in an Alpine proglacial area",2011,"Geoderma","165","1",,"106","117",,,10.1016/j.geoderma.2011.07.010,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051697200&partnerID=40&md5=54af3bffb37da84975d8d61350e3a79e","Department of Geography, University of Zurich, Zurich, 8057, Switzerland; ETH Zurich, Institute for Geotechnical Engineering, Zurich, 8093, Switzerland; Istituto Sperimentale per lo Studio e la Difesa del Suolo, Centro di ricerca per l'Agrobiologia e la Pedologia, Piazza D'Azeglio 30, 50121 Firenze, Italy","Mavris, C., Department of Geography, University of Zurich, Zurich, 8057, Switzerland; Plötze, M., ETH Zurich, Institute for Geotechnical Engineering, Zurich, 8093, Switzerland; Mirabella, A., Istituto Sperimentale per lo Studio e la Difesa del Suolo, Centro di ricerca per l'Agrobiologia e la Pedologia, Piazza D'Azeglio 30, 50121 Firenze, Italy; Giaccai, D., Istituto Sperimentale per lo Studio e la Difesa del Suolo, Centro di ricerca per l'Agrobiologia e la Pedologia, Piazza D'Azeglio 30, 50121 Firenze, Italy; Valboa, G., Istituto Sperimentale per lo Studio e la Difesa del Suolo, Centro di ricerca per l'Agrobiologia e la Pedologia, Piazza D'Azeglio 30, 50121 Firenze, Italy; Egli s, M., Department of Geography, University of Zurich, Zurich, 8057, Switzerland","As a consequence of global warming, additional areas will become ice-free and subject to weathering and soil formation. The most evident soil changes in the Alps will occur in proglacial areas where young soils will continuously develop due to glacier retreat. Little is known about the initial stages of weathering and soil formation, i.e. during the first decades of soil genesis. In this study, we investigated clay minerals formation during a time span 0-150 years in the proglacial area of Morteratsch (Swiss Alps). The soils developed on granitic till and were Lithic Leptosols.Mineralogical measurements of the clay (<. 2. μm) and fine silt fraction (2-32. μm) were carried out using XRD (X-ray Diffraction) and DRIFT (Diffuse Reflectance Infrared Fourier Transform). Fast formation and transformation mechanisms were measured in the clay fraction. The decreasing proportion of trioctahedral phases with time confirmed active chemical weathering. Since the start of soil formation, smectite was actively formed. Some smectite (low charge) and vermiculite (high charge) was however already present in the parent material. Main source of smectite formation was biotite, hornblende and probably plagioclase. Furthermore, irregularly and regularly interstratified clay minerals (mica-HIV or mica-vermiculite) were formed immediately after the start of moraine exposure to weathering. In addition, hydroxy-interlayered smectite (HIS) as a transitory weathering product from mica to smectite was detected. Furthermore, since the start of soil evolution, kaolinite was progressively formed. In the silt fraction, only little changes could be detected; i.e. some formation of an interstratified mica-HIV or mica-vermiculite phase.The detected clay mineral formation and transformation mechanisms within this short time span confirmed the high reactivity of freshly exposed sediments, even in a cryic environment. © 2011 Elsevier B.V.","Alps; Clay minerals; Mica; Proglacial area; Smectite; Soil chronosequence","Active chemicals; Alps; Clay fractions; Clay-mineral formation; Diffuse reflectance; Fine silt; Glacier retreat; High reactivity; Initial stages; Parent materials; Proglacial; Smectites; Soil changes; Soil chronosequence; Soil evolutions; Soil formations; Soil genesis; Swiss Alps; Time span; Transformation mechanisms; XRD; Anoxic sediments; Fourier transforms; Global warming; Kaolin; Kaolinite; Mica; Minerals; Silt; Soil mechanics; X ray diffraction; Weathering; alpine environment; chemical weathering; chronosequence; clay mineral; glacier retreat; global warming; mica; parent material; pedogenesis; proglacial environment; silt; till; transformation; Alps; Switzerland; Human immunodeficiency virus",,,,,,"Anderson, R.S., Modeling the tor-dotted crests, bedrock edges, and parabolic profiles of high alpine surfaces of the Wind River Range, Wyoming (2002) Geomorphology, 46, pp. 35-58; Anderson, S.P., Drever, J.I., Frost, C.D., Holden, P., Chemical weathering in the foreland of a retreating glacier (2000) Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta, 64, pp. 1173-1189; Aoudjit, H., Robert, M., Elsass, F., Curmi, P., Detailed study of smectite genesis in granite saprolites by analytical electron microscopy (1995) Clay Minerals, 30, pp. 135-148; Arn, K., Hosein, R., Föllmi, K.B., Steinmann, P., Aubert, D., Kramers, J., Strontium isotope systematics in two glaciated crystalline catchments: Rhone and Oberaar glaciers (Swiss Alps) (2003) Swiss Bulletin of Mineralogy and Petrology, 83, pp. 273-283; Arocena, J.M., Pawluk, S., Dudas, M.J., Layer charge of expandable 2:1 phyllosilicates in selected parent materials of some Canadian soils (1994) Canadian Journal of Soil Science, 74, pp. 291-299; Barnhisel, R.I., Bertsch, P.M., Chlorite and hydroxy-interlayered vermiculite and smectite (1989) Soil Science Society of America, SSSA Book Series, 1, pp. 729-788. , Madison, WI, USA, J.B. Dixon, S.B. Weed (Eds.) Minerals in Soil Environments; Bétard, F., Caner, L., Gunnell, Y., Bourgeon, G., Illite neoformation in plagioclase during weathering: evidence from semi-arid Northeast Brazil (2009) Geoderma, 152, pp. 53-62; Bishop, J., Madejova, J., Komadel, P., Fröschl, H., The influence of structural Fe, Al and Mg of the infrared OH bands in spectra of dioctahedral smectites (2002) Clay Minerals, 37, pp. 607-616; Brantley, S.L., Megonigal, J.P., Scatena, F.N., Balogh-Brunstad, Z., Barnes, R.T., Bruns, M.A., Van Cappellen, P., Yoo, K., Twelve testable hypotheses on the geobiology of weathering (2011) Geobiology; Büchi, H., (1987), Geologie und Petrographie der Bernina IX. Das Gebiet zwischen Pontresina und dem Morteratschgletscher. Unpubliziert Diplomarbeit Universität ZürichBüchi, H., Der variskische Magmatismus in der östlichen Bernina (Graubünden, Schweiz) (1994) Schweizerische Mineralogische und Petrographische Mitteilungen, 74, pp. 359-371; Burga, C., Vegetation development on the glacier forefield Morteratsch (Switzerland) (1999) Applied Vegetation Science, 2, pp. 17-24; Burga, C.A., Krüsi, B., Egli, M., Wernli, M., Elsener, S., Ziefle, M., Mavris, C., Plant succession and soil development on the foreland of the Morteratsch glacier (Pontresina, Switzerland): straight forward or chaotic? (2010) Flora, 205, pp. 561-576; Caner, L., Joussein, E., Salvador-Blanes, S., Hubert, F., Schlicht, J.F., Duigou, N., Short-time clay-mineral evolution in a soil chronosequence in Oleron Island (France) (2010) Journal of Plant Nutrition and Soil Science, 173, pp. 591-600; Conen, F., Yakutin, M.V., Zumbrunn, T., Leifeld, J., Organic carbon and microbial biomass in two soil development chronosequences following glacial retreat (2007) European Journal of Soil Science, 58, pp. 758-762; Cox, N.J., On the relationship between bedrock lowering and regolith thickness (1980) Earth Surface Processes, 5, pp. 271-274; D'Amico, C., Innocenti, F., Sassi, F.P., (1998), Magmatismo e Metamorfismo. Ed. UTET, TorinoDietrich, W.E., Perron, J.T., The search for a topographic signature of life (2006) Nature, 439, pp. 411-418; Dreher, P., Niederbudde, E.A., Characterization of expandable layer silicates in humic-ferralic cambisols (umbrept) derived from biotite and hornblende (2000) Journal of Plant Nutrition Soil Science, 163, pp. 447-453; Dümig, A., Smittenberg, R., Kögel-Knabner, I., Concurrent evolution of organic and mineral components during initial soil development after retreat of the Damma glacier, Switzerland (2011) Geoderma, 163, pp. 83-94; EDI (Eidgenössisches Departement des Innern) Hydrologischer Atlas der Schweiz (HADES) (1992) Landeshydrologie 